article.description: Chris Paul, Eric Williams and Kyle Visser each scored 15 points to lead the Demon Deacons past Yale 99-72.
article.headline: Five Wake players score in double figures
article.linkText: New No. 1 Wake forest spanks Yale
article.story: WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) -- After years of watching instate powers Duke and North Carolina sit atop the national rankings, Wake Forest has finally reached No. 1. On Monday night, the Demon Deacons looked determined to stay there. Chris Paul, Eric Williams and Kyle Visser each scored 15 points to lead Wake Forest past Yale 99-72. Chris Ellis added 14 points for the Demon Deacons (3-0), who had five players in double figures. They had little trouble on offense in the first half and maintained a comfortable lead throughout against the Bulldogs (1-2). Hours earlier, the Demon Deacons climbed into the top spot of The Associated Press Top 25 for the first time in school history. They jumped past Kansas from No. 2 after the Jayhawks trailed much of the way in their season-opening 68-61 win against Vermont. Wake Forest had been ranked No. 2 for 12 weeks -- 10 coming in Tim Duncan's senior season of 1996-97 -- which was the third most for a school that had never reached the top spot. Paul -- the preseason All-America point guard -- said the ranking was an honor but playing as the nation's top-ranked team felt like "business as usual." "The games still feel the same," Paul said. "You have to play the same teams. I can understand if it was the end of the season, but we're only three games into the season so it really doesn't mean much." The Demon Deacons will surely be challenged to keep that ranking. They opened the season with double-digit wins against George Washington and Virginia Commonwealth in the Preseason NIT, advancing to Wednesday's semifinals against Providence. After leaving New York, they travel to No. 5 Illinois. "We're finding out a lot about ourselves after these three games," Wake Forest coach Skip Prosser said, "and we'll know a whole lot more by the time next (week) rolls around." Their debut at No. 1 was marked by a solid first half that helped them to a 17-point lead at the break. Nine players scored in the first 14 minutes, with the Demon Deacons scoring 58 points and shooting 48 percent from the floor. They did it from everywhere on the court. Paul and Justin Gray combined to hit six 3-pointers. Trent Strickland completed two three-point plays late in the half, including a hanging reverse layup off an offensive rebound. The Demon Deacons also made their free throws, something they had trouble doing in their first two games. After missing 25 foul shots in two games, they went 16-for-18 in the first half and 23-of-30 for the game. Though Yale pulled within 12 early in the second half, the Demon Deacons were never in danger of losing a November game for just the second time in five years. They had 12 dunks -- four by Williams and two by seldom-used reserve Richard Joyce -- and shot 50 percent for the third straight game. They also scored 44 points in the paint and had a 47-30 edge on the glass. The biggest danger they faced all night was when Prosser nearly slipped walking out of the locker room before the game. "I thought Wake Forest was the No. 1 team going into the season," Yale coach James Jones said. "The only option you have is to go out and play as hard as possible." It wasn't a perfect night. Wake Forest allowed Yale to shoot 45 percent -- Prosser conceded the game was hardly a defensive gem -- and again made too many turnovers. After committing 20 in each of the first two games, they had 18 more Monday. But they had few complaints about the offense. "We're really sharing the ball," Williams said. "Nobody's hogging anything. The ball's being spread around by everybody." Wake Forest got a boost from Ellis, a junior who missed the opener and much of the second game after he was suspended for violating team rules. The 6-9 forward, the son of former NBA player and 3-point ace Dale Ellis, even hit two 3s -- the first of his career -- in the final four minutes. "He's been practicing hard and it was nice to be able to reward him with some significant playing time," Prosser said. "He's going to have to help us if we're going to go where we'd like to go." Casey Hughes had 20 points and 10 rebounds to lead Yale, and Edwin Draughan added 19 points.
